{"parse":{"title":"Leonard Roy Harmon","pageid":32932815,"revid":855213506,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em;width:25.5em;border-spacing:2px;\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color:#C3D6EF;\"><span class=\"fn\">Leonard Roy Harmon</span></th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;border-bottom: 1px solid #aaa;; line-height: 1.5em\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:USS_Harmon_Poster.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"USS Harmon Poster.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/39/USS_Harmon_Poster.jpg/220px-USS_Harmon_Poster.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"283\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/39/USS_Harmon_Poster.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"292\" data-file-height=\"375\" /></a><div style=\"font-size: 100%\">A 1943 poster in honor of Harmon.</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Born</th><td>\n<span style=\"display:none\">(<span class=\"bday\">1917-01-21</span>)</span>January 21, 1917<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Cuero,_Texas\" title=\"Cuero, Texas\">Cuero, Texas</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Died</th><td>\nNovember 23, 1942<span style=\"display:none\">(1942-11-23)</span> (aged&#160;25)<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Guadalcanal\" title=\"Guadalcanal\">Guadalcanal</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Solomon_Islands\" title=\"Solomon Islands\">Solomon Islands</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Allegiance</th><td>\n<span class=\"flagicon\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg/23px-Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"12\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg/35px-Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f5/Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg/46px-Flag_of_the_United_States_%281912-1959%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1900\" data-file-height=\"1000\" />&#160;</span><a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States of America</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Service/<wbr />branch</th><td>\n<span class=\"flagicon\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg/23px-Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg.png\" width=\"23\" height=\"18\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg/35px-Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/02/Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg/46px-Flag_of_the_United_States_Navy_%28official%29.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1280\" data-file-height=\"1008\" />&#160;</span><a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Navy\" title=\"United States Navy\">United States Navy</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Years&#160;of service</th><td>\n1939\u20131942</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Rank</th><td>\nMessman First Class</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Unit</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/USS_San_Francisco_(CA-38)\" title=\"USS San Francisco (CA-38)\">USS&#160;<i>San Francisco</i></a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Battles/wars</th><td>\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a>\n</p>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Naval_Battle_of_Guadalcanal\" title=\"Naval Battle of Guadalcanal\">Naval Battle of Guadalcanal</a></li></ul>\n</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"padding-right: 1em\">Awards</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Navy Cross ribbon.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg/22px-Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"6\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg/33px-Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/3e/Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg/44px-Navy_Cross_ribbon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"279\" /></a> <a href=\"/wiki/Navy_Cross\" title=\"Navy Cross\">Navy Cross</a><br /><a href=\"/wiki/File:Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Purple Heart ribbon.svg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg/22px-Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg.png\" width=\"22\" height=\"6\" class=\"thumbborder\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg/33px-Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg/44px-Purple_Heart_ribbon.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"1024\" data-file-height=\"279\" /></a> <a href=\"/wiki/Purple_Heart\" title=\"Purple Heart\">Purple Heart</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b> Leonard Roy Harmon</b> (January 21, 1917&#8211;November 13, 1942) was a black American sailor who died in action during <a href=\"/wiki/World_War_II\" title=\"World War II\">World War II</a> and was posthumously awarded the <a href=\"/wiki/Navy_Cross_(United_States)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navy Cross (United States)\">Navy Cross</a> for his valor.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Life\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Life</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Honors\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Honors</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Navy_Cross_citation\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Navy Cross citation</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#External_links\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Life\">Life</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Leonard_Roy_Harmon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Life\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Harmon was born in <a href=\"/wiki/Cuero,_Texas\" title=\"Cuero, Texas\">Cuero, Texas</a>, was 22 years of age when he enlisted in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Navy\" title=\"United States Navy\">U. S. Navy</a> in June 1939.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Memorial_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Memorial-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Valor_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Valor-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> He reported for training in <a href=\"/wiki/Norfolk,_Virginia\" title=\"Norfolk, Virginia\">Norfolk, Virginia</a> before reporting for duty on the <a href=\"/wiki/USS_San_Francisco_(CA-38)\" title=\"USS San Francisco (CA-38)\">USS&#160;<i>San Francisco</i></a> on October 28, 1939.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burns_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burns-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> He trained as a Mess Attendant, one of the few jobs available to black men in the navy at that time.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Memorial_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Memorial-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The basic job description consisted of serving food to officers and crew aboard ship. However, like all members of a ship\u2019s crew they were also trained in <a href=\"/wiki/Damage_control\" title=\"Damage control\">damage control</a> and had stations to report to during <a href=\"/wiki/General_quarters\" title=\"General quarters\">general quarters</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>During his service he became a Mess Attendant First Class and was serving aboard the <a href=\"/wiki/USS_San_Francisco_(CA-38)\" title=\"USS San Francisco (CA-38)\">USS&#160;<i>San Francisco</i></a> when on November 12, 1942 he was killed in action. During the course of the <a href=\"/wiki/Naval_Battle_of_Guadalcanal\" title=\"Naval Battle of Guadalcanal\">Naval Battle of Guadalcanal</a> he was assigned to assist pharmacist's mate Lyndford Bondsteel in caring for the wounded.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> While the ship was being raked by enemy gunfire, Harmon helped evacuate the wounded to a <a href=\"/wiki/Dressing_station\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Dressing station\">dressing station</a>. While doing so he deliberately interposed himself between Bondsteel and enemy gunfire in order to protect his wounded shipmate.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burns_5-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burns-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> This action resulted in his death.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burns_5-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burns-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Honors\">Honors</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Leonard_Roy_Harmon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Honors\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Harmon was awarded the <a href=\"/wiki/Navy_Cross_(United_States)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Navy Cross (United States)\">Navy Cross</a> posthumously. Additionally, two ships were named in his honor. <a href=\"/wiki/HMS_Aylmer_(K463)\" title=\"HMS Aylmer (K463)\">HMS <i>Aylmer</i></a> had been provisionally named <a href=\"/wiki/USS_Harmon_(DE-72)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"USS Harmon (DE-72)\">USS <i>Harmon</i></a> (DE-72) but was transferred to the Royal Navy prior to completion.  The <a href=\"/wiki/USS_Harmon_(DE-678)\" title=\"USS Harmon (DE-678)\">USS <i>Harmon</i></a> (DE-678) served from 1943 to 1947 and remained in the Reserve Fleet until 1967; it was the first US warship to be named for an <a href=\"/wiki/African_American\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"African American\">African American</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-usnhc_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-usnhc-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> Harmon's heroism was also commemorated by the naming and dedication of Harmon Hall, bachelor enlisted quarters at <a href=\"/wiki/Naval_Air_Station_North_Island\" title=\"Naval Air Station North Island\">Naval Air Station North Island</a>, on July 29, 1975, and with a state historical marker placed at the Cuero Municipal Park in 1977.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Burns_5-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Burns-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg/220px-%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"217\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg/330px-%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg/440px-%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3000\" data-file-height=\"2964\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:%22DEMOCRACY_IN_ACTION%22_No.IV_-_NARA_-_535634.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>An <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Office_of_War_Information\" title=\"United States Office of War Information\">Office of War Information</a> poster from 1943 by <a href=\"/wiki/Charles_Alston\" title=\"Charles Alston\">Charles Alston</a> depicting  Harmon and the ship named in his honor.</div></div></div>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Navy_Cross_citation\">Navy Cross citation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Leonard_Roy_Harmon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Navy Cross citation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<blockquote><p>The President of the United States of America takes pride in presenting the Navy Cross (Posthumously) to Mess Attendant First Class Leonard Roy Harmon, United States Navy, for extraordinary heroism and devotion to duty in action against the enemy while serving on board the Heavy Cruiser U.S.S. SAN FRANCISCO (CA-38), during action against enemy Japanese naval forces near Savo Island in the Solomon Islands on the night of on 12\u201313 November 1942. With persistent disregard of his own personal safety, Mess Attendant First Class Harmon rendered invaluable assistance in caring for the wounded and assisting them to a dressing station. In addition to displaying unusual loyalty in behalf of the injured Executive Officer, he deliberately exposed himself to hostile gunfire in order to protect a shipmate and, as a result of this courageous deed, was killed in action. His heroic spirit of self-sacrifice, maintained above and beyond the call of duty, was in keeping with the highest traditions of the United States Naval Service. He gallantly gave his life for his country.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Valor_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Valor-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>\n<div style=\"clear:both;\"></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Leonard_Roy_Harmon&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/pers-us/uspers-h/l-harmon.htm\">http://www.history.navy.mil/photos/pers-us/uspers-h/l-harmon.htm</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Johnson Publishing Company (1952-11-13). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=w7oDAAAAMBAJ&amp;lpg=PA10&amp;dq=Leonard%20Roy%20Harmon&amp;pg=PA3#v=onepage&amp;q=Leonard%20Roy%20Harmon&amp;f=false\">\"Today in Negro History\"</a>. <i>Jet</i>. <b>III</b> (3). p.&#160;10.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Jet&amp;rft.atitle=Today+in+Negro+History&amp;rft.volume=III&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=10&amp;rft.date=1952-11-13&amp;rft.au=Johnson+Publishing+Company&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3Dw7oDAAAAMBAJ%26lpg%3DPA10%26dq%3DLeonard%2520Roy%2520Harmon%26pg%3DPA3%23v%3Donepage%26q%3DLeonard%2520Roy%2520Harmon%26f%3Dfalse&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALeonard+Roy+Harmon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Memorial-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Memorial_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Memorial_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://usssanfrancisco.org/the-stories/leonard-harmon-usn/\">\"DESTROYER ESCORT NAMED IN HONOR OF CUERO NEGRO WHO DIED HERO ABOARD COURAGEOUS U.S.S. SAN FRANCISCO\"</a>. <i>The Cuero Record Newspaper</i> (274). <a href=\"/wiki/DeWitt_County,_Texas\" title=\"DeWitt County, Texas\">DeWitt County, Texas</a>. November 17, 1943<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">16 August</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Cuero+Record+Newspaper&amp;rft.atitle=DESTROYER+ESCORT+NAMED+IN+HONOR+OF+CUERO+NEGRO+WHO+DIED+HERO+ABOARD+COURAGEOUS+U.S.S.+SAN+FRANCISCO&amp;rft.issue=274&amp;rft.date=1943-11-17&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fusssanfrancisco.org%2Fthe-stories%2Fleonard-harmon-usn%2F&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALeonard+Roy+Harmon\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Valor-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Valor_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Valor_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://valor.militarytimes.com/hero/20495\">\"Leonard Roy Harmon\"</a>. <i>The Hall of Valor Project</i>. Sightline Media Group<span class=\"reference